    "pathophysiology": "Hematogenous dissemination of M. tuberculosis from primary pulmonary focus (Ghon focus) to liver via hepatic artery. Organisms engulfed by Kupffer cells; if cell-mediated immunity inadequate, organisms multiply within macrophages forming caseating granulomas. Granulomas consist of central caseous necrosis surrounded by epithelioid histiocytes, Langhans giant cells, and lymphocytes. Cholestasis results from bile duct compression by granulomas and periportal inflammation. Hepatocyte injury arises from surrounding granulomatous inflammation and cytotoxic T-cell response. In miliary TB, countless small granulomas throughout liver parenchyma.",
